title: Phillips 66 Partners’ Losing Streak Continues on Tuesday, July 14
text:
Phillips 66 Partners’ Losing Streak Continues on Tuesday, July 14 By Kurt Gallon 39 minutes ago  
( Continued from Prior Part ) Top losers 
In the last part of this series, we saw the top five midstream MLP (master limited partnership) gainers on Tuesday, July 14. In this part, we’ll discuss the top five midstream MLP losers on the same day. Enable Midstream Partners 
Enable Midstream Partners (ENBL) was the top loser among midstream MLPs at the end of trading on Tuesday, July 14. It fell 5.41% yesterday. Enable Midstream provides natural gas gathering, processing, transportation, and storage services. It has returned -25.99% YTD (year-to-date). Phillips 66 Partners 
Next on our list of the top five midstream MLP losers on July 14 is Phillips 66 Partners (PSXP). Its losing streak continued on Tuesday. After a 3.92% fall on Monday July 14, Phillips 66 fell 4.09% yesterday. The stock has returned -7.88% YTD. It owns and operates primarily fee-based crude oil, refined petroleum product, and NGL (natural gas liquid) pipelines and terminals and other midstream assets. Other losers 
Rose Rock Midstream (RRMS), Valero Energy Partners (VLP), and Crestwood Midstream Partners (CMLP) were among the top five midstream MLP losers on Tuesday, July 14. They fell 2.53%, 1.34%, and 1.19% in the last trading session, respectively. They’ve returned -0.84%, 13.73%, and -23.12% YTD, respectively. 
Valero Energy Partners’ solid YTD market performance can be attributed to its strong distribution growth. Its 1Q15 distribution grew by 31% YoY (year-over-year) during 1Q14. Valero Energy Partners was formed by Valero Energy (VLO) to own, operate, develop, and acquire crude oil and refined petroleum products pipelines, terminals, and other transportation and logistics assets. 
The Alerian MLP ETF (AMLP) is comprised of 25 midstream MLPs. It has returned -8.90% YTD. Crestwood Midstream accounts for ~1.36% of AMLP. For context, the upstream energy company heavy SPDR S&P Oil & Gas Exploration & Production ETF (XOP) has returned -5.52% YTD.
